To evaluate the ability of TM-CDs to chelate iron, TM-CDs were compared with several representative traditional iron-chelating agents. As shown in Fig. 3c, EDTA-2Na, sodium citrate [54], and sodium gluconate [55] were added to TM-CDs, and the result showed that three traditional iron-chelating agents did not affect the fluorescence intensity of TM-CDs. Firstly, the TM-CDs solution and the Fe3+ solution were mixed evenly for 6 h, and then three traditional iron-chelating agents (same concentration as TM-CDs) were added into it and mixed for 6 h. As shown in the above figure, the addition of EDTA-2Na, sodium citrate, and sodium gluconate did not lead to the fluorescence recovery of the TM-CDs, indicating the three traditional iron-chelating agents could not bind Fe3+ on the surface of TM-CDs. The result showed that TM-CDs was much stronger than the three traditional iron-chelating agents in chelating iron. To further demonstrate the chelating ability of TM-CDs for Fe3+, we evaluated the chelating behavior and maximum chelating capacity of TM-CDs for Fe3+ using Langmuir isotherm and Freundlich isotherm (Fig. 3d). The chelation rate of TM-CDs for Fe3+ was significantly increased with the initial concentration of Fe3+ improved. This phenomenon is because the higher initial concentration shortens the mean free path in the process and increases the role of Fe3+ with the chelation sites on TM-CDs. The Langmuir isotherm fitted better than the Freundlich isotherm, which indicated that the sites of chelating Fe3+ on TM-CDs surface were monolayer and uniform [28]. Fig. 3e and 3f show the linear fitting forms of Langmuir isotherm and Freundlich isotherm, respectively. The corresponding parameters were obtained according to the fitting results (Table 1
                           ). It was reported that the maximum chelating capacity of hydrogels derived from cellulose nanocrystals decorated with carbon dots (C-dot/CNCs) for Fe3+ was 50 mg g−1 
                           [56]. Table 1 shows that the maximum chelating capacity of TM-CDs for Fe3+ was 154.56 mg g−1. The R2 of linear fitting of Langmuir isotherm and Freundlich isotherm were 0.9942 and 0.9692, respectively. The value of 1/n indicates the favorable degree of chelating process, and 0 < 1/n < 1 is considered as the favorable chelating process. Therefore, it is proved that TM-CDs has excellent ability to chelate Fe3+.
